1
00:00:00,695 --> 00:00:02,617
The curtain looks the same

2
00:00:02,836 --> 00:00:05,617
Where we used to shower and wash

3
00:00:05,922 --> 00:00:07,266
We had put it up for that purpose

4
00:00:07,291 --> 00:00:09,844
Or for anyone doing <i>wudu</i> [ablution] for prayer as well

5
00:00:10,898 --> 00:00:13,758
And the smell reached inside, even to the third room

6
00:00:14,648 --> 00:00:19,039
Meaning whoever wanted to use the toilet or wash

7
00:00:19,064 --> 00:00:21,227
Or whoever wanted to do <i>wudu</i> [ablution] to pray and make supplication

8
00:00:21,313 --> 00:00:22,344
Would come here

9
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:29,273
Interviewer: Did the bathroom break down so you couldn’t use it?

10
00:00:29,758 --> 00:00:31,211
No, it didn’t break down

11
00:00:32,117 --> 00:00:33,539
Interviewer: Was the water available at all times?

12
00:00:33,688 --> 00:00:35,117
Yes, it was always available

13
00:00:36,531 --> 00:00:39,859
Interviewer: Tell me about cleaning supplies, soap and so on.

14
00:00:40,039 --> 00:00:41,047
Only soap was available

15
00:00:41,242 --> 00:00:45,016
Scrubbing gloves for the showers weren’t available, and we couldn’t shower daily

16
00:00:46,195 --> 00:00:48,046
Only every three or four days

17
00:00:48,071 --> 00:00:49,867
And sometimes every fifteen days

18
00:00:50,359 --> 00:00:51,391
That’s how we used to shower

19
00:00:53,148 --> 00:00:58,031
Interviewer: Did you feel privacy when you went to the toilet?

20
00:00:58,219 --> 00:01:01,125
Or could people hear sounds from inside?

21
00:01:01,453 --> 00:01:03,586
And did you suffer from that while washing or showering?

22
00:01:03,664 --> 00:01:06,039
There was no privacy

23
00:01:06,064 --> 00:01:08,500
And that was the reason we put this curtain here

24
00:01:08,969 --> 00:01:10,906
It was hard for us even to use the toilet

25
00:01:12,617 --> 00:01:17,125
Interviewer: Were you harassed by prisoners while you were in the toilet?

26
00:01:17,258 --> 00:01:18,258
Did anyone harass you?

27
00:01:18,297 --> 00:01:19,320
Okay, what happened?

28
00:01:21,888 --> 00:01:26,295
An argument broke out among us and our shouting got louder

29
00:01:27,443 --> 00:01:28,443
Interviewer: What was the reason?

30
00:01:28,468 --> 00:01:31,724
Over access to the bathroom to use the toilet

31
00:01:31,779 --> 00:01:34,529
It wasn’t just me, the other prisoners did too

32
00:01:34,935 --> 00:01:39,498
It was hard for everyone to use the toilet, do <i>wudu</i> [ablution], or shower

33
00:01:40,513 --> 00:01:42,959
Someone would sit here to keep count and police the prisoners

34
00:01:43,006 --> 00:01:45,834
If a prisoner went in more than once to use the toilet or do <i>wudu</i> [ablution]

35
00:01:57,006 --> 00:02:02,826
Interviewer: What changes have happened to the bathroom since then?

36
00:02:03,162 --> 00:02:05,154
Nothing at all has changed

37
00:02:05,709 --> 00:02:09,076
The bathroom is the same, and the sink is the same

38
00:02:09,576 --> 00:02:11,029
We used to try to look through that window

39
00:02:12,224 --> 00:02:14,279
We would look out of it toward the alley

40
00:02:14,388 --> 00:02:16,849
And watch the civilians going back and forth

41
00:02:17,928 --> 00:02:20,998
We used to see the children playing in the neighboring houses

42
00:02:21,023 --> 00:02:22,435
We saw all that through that window

43
00:02:26,748 --> 00:02:30,224
When I came, I heard children’s voices

44
00:02:30,912 --> 00:02:31,997
I figured they were kids

45
00:02:32,022 --> 00:02:33,044
So I snuck a look from here

46
00:02:33,154 --> 00:02:36,459
Through a small opening in that metal

47
00:02:36,974 --> 00:02:39,209
And I saw children standing in the next room by the window

48
00:02:39,795 --> 00:02:40,810
And they were crying

49
00:02:43,357 --> 00:02:44,912
And I felt afraid

50
00:02:45,365 --> 00:02:48,068
So I sat still in my place without moving or making a sound

51
00:02:48,873 --> 00:02:51,271
Someone asked me what I’d seen, and I said nothing

52
00:02:51,638 --> 00:02:53,717
I stayed silent and frozen in place

53
00:02:55,480 --> 00:02:58,683
Interviewer: Do you mean the prisoners’ children?

54
00:02:58,948 --> 00:03:00,909
Or who were those children?

55
00:03:01,331 --> 00:03:03,651
Their mother was detained for possessing cigarettes

56
00:03:05,862 --> 00:03:07,409
So her children were watching from the window

57
00:03:07,456 --> 00:03:08,683
Their mother was being beaten in front of them

58
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:10,511
They were flogging her here

59
00:03:11,221 --> 00:03:12,245
In the middle of the yard

60
00:03:12,698 --> 00:03:14,316
And her little children were watching her

61
00:03:17,105 --> 00:03:21,011
Interviewer: What kind of sounds did you hear while you were in this room?

62
00:03:21,276 --> 00:03:23,276
Did you hear sounds from outside?

63
00:03:23,612 --> 00:03:25,667
And was that late at night?

64
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:30,401
No, there were no sounds at night

65
00:03:30,464 --> 00:03:32,487
And there were no sounds of beating

66
00:03:33,073 --> 00:03:39,066
But anyone who came on the charge of passing information over the phone

67
00:03:39,105 --> 00:03:40,581
About the security forces, for example

68
00:03:41,448 --> 00:03:43,831
They would bring him to the hall to hold him to account

69
00:03:43,980 --> 00:03:47,253
And they would flog him or beat him

70
00:03:49,073 --> 00:03:52,769
Interviewer: Did they ask you about the items you had stolen during the torture?

71
00:03:52,794 --> 00:03:54,917
And how did they know you were the thief when you were this young?

72
00:03:54,964 --> 00:03:57,018
And what items did you steal from your uncle’s house?

73
00:03:57,050 --> 00:03:59,167
They said someone from the area had reported me

74
00:03:59,519 --> 00:04:00,769
Saying that I had taken the items

75
00:04:01,284 --> 00:04:02,714
They asked me where the items were, and I said I didn’t know

76
00:04:03,573 --> 00:04:06,534
So they started torturing me and beating me

77
00:04:06,714 --> 00:04:11,464
And they threatened to burn me with cooking oil

78
00:04:12,511 --> 00:04:14,753
And they kept torturing me

79
00:04:15,597 --> 00:04:18,511
And beating me with shoes and slaps

80
00:04:18,605 --> 00:04:20,612
And even kicking or hitting me with a bamboo stick

81
00:04:21,316 --> 00:04:22,956
They tortured me until the very last moment

82
00:04:23,917 --> 00:04:25,776
They burned me here, in this spot

83
00:04:26,511 --> 00:04:27,769
The burn mark is still there

84
00:04:28,237 --> 00:04:29,136
Interviewer: What did they burn you with?

85
00:04:29,161 --> 00:04:30,792
With a metal rod

86
00:04:31,675 --> 00:04:32,800
They burned me with it here

87
00:04:35,159 --> 00:04:36,284
And then they left me

88
00:04:36,448 --> 00:04:39,651
After I’d confessed to stealing the items and where they were

89
00:04:41,175 --> 00:04:42,441
Interviewer: What items did you take?

90
00:04:42,566 --> 00:04:43,784
A whole home’s belongings

91
00:04:43,809 --> 00:04:44,526
Interviewer: Like what?

92
00:04:44,551 --> 00:04:46,198
The household furniture

93
00:04:46,558 --> 00:04:47,714
Interviewer: Did you move it to your house?

94
00:04:47,745 --> 00:04:48,698
Yes

95
00:04:49,644 --> 00:04:51,573
Interviewer: Did they later confiscate it from your home?
Witness: No

96
00:04:54,698 --> 00:04:56,612
Interviewer: Did they need it themselves?

97
00:04:57,347 --> 00:05:00,948
When they confiscate a house, they consider it to have become theirs

98
00:05:01,941 --> 00:05:05,878
For example, if they confiscated a home of one of the <i>Rawafid</i> [pejorative for Shia], they considered it theirs

99
00:05:06,519 --> 00:05:07,636
Either they used it to live in

100
00:05:07,995 --> 00:05:09,839
Or they took the household belongings as spoils

101
00:05:10,675 --> 00:05:13,761
And they sold them in a large place designated for that
